I know this is an unpopular subject  but the truth is when a person becomes disabled after having been a working and contributing member of society their whole life, it is going to take them possibly several years to get approved for SS/SSI or SSDI. It is not right. This is a close personal issue for me because I worked for 30 years before becoming seriously injured and now cannot work regular gainful work. I was lucky enough to live in a state that did provide welfare benefits. I am not stating that we should just let everyone have money no matter what but there are people who are really in need and nothing is being done about this 48 of 50 states. What happens to these people? Suicide? Depression? Anxiety? Feelings of shame and guilt and wondering what you could have done differently to avoid this? By the time you finally do get approved for the benefits you worked your whole life for, you are no longer the same person, you are an even much more broke version of yourself. I live in Minnesota and the GA benefit is 203 dollars, 30% of that goes to rent, and the rest is all you have to live on for a whole month. Thank god it is something, but you go without many things you really should have access to and it spirals you down into a really dark place. Many people where I live spiraled down into drugs because of it. I am fortunate that this is not my case but I see these things first hand everyday of what started as just an injury makes your life unrecognizable.

So yes, we need to start fixing the problems in our own country and that starts with helping people with very basic things so that the fabric of our society does not continue to disintegrate at an alarming pace because people know the truth, that no one in Washington actually gives a **** about them. Q62: I think the top priorities should be affordable and available housing, more assistance for food, and curbing inflation by increasing taxes for the 10% wealthiest.

I'd like to see them pass an actual budget, preferably a fiscally responsible one. I'd like to see them address immigration reform and boarder security. I'd also like to see them prevent us from getting involved in foreign military conflicts.

I believe leaders should tackle climate change. I'd also like to see political leaders do something to address polarization and how politics generally runs, but that will never happen because the steps they could probably take--changing campaign finance laws, etc--are not in their short term interest. Finally, I wish leaders would pass serious budgets. I'm not a fiscal policy hawk by any means, but I think it is pie in the sky to think we never have to pay attention to deficits or the long-term commitments we have already made. It seems that everyone agrees the debt can become an issue at some point, so let's have serious conversations about military spending, healthcare costs and the other major drivers of federal debt. The things we seem to fight about--social safety nets etc--are not what is causing the damage to our financial health. I know this is largely seen as a conservative position to even talk about debt. But it really isn't. The change in interest rates and the global environment have made the costs of debt more serious. The disfunction politically also makes the US look like less of a secure place to park money and those things *could* really have an impact.

comments:
I found the study interesting. In particular the video that says "1 in 5 women experience a complication." It was nice to see in the fact check that the statistic was false or misleading. But these sorts of studies are really hard to take. I believe in following facts, not partisan agendas. I don't have a "team" and don't really understand why people would feel so strongly identified with one side or the other. I want good policy wherever it comes from.

Back to the stat though, I can imagine a world in which the 1 in 5 stat is literally true but gets twisted by these super pacs or lobbying groups or whatever they are. Like what kind of complications are we talking about? What gets defined "as an abortion or not"? Sometimes there is just practical reality (I don't believe whatever special categorization you want to have makes the 10 year old terminating her pregnancy not an abortion) and I generally hear medication abortion is safe, but what those things mean statistically and whether you can put together talking points that are true in some sense to say "1 in 5 women experience a complication" is often another matter. There is a lack of intellectual honesty among many of these groups. They aren't trying to be objective or to craft good policy. They are trying to get what they want.
